SIMPLE: riches
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Riches
<hw>Rich"es</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>richesse</ets>, F. <ets>richesse</ets>, from <ets>riche</ets> rich,
of German origin. See <er>Rich</er>,<pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>That which makes one rich; an abundance of land, goods, money, or
other property; wealth; opulence; affluence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Riches</qex> do not consist in having more gold and silver,
but in having more in proportion, than our neighbors.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which appears rich, sumptuous, precious, or the
like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>riche</qex> of heaven's pavement, trodden gold.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Richesse</xex>, the older form of this word, was in
the singular number. The form <xex>riches</xex>, however, is plural in
appearance, and has now come to be used as a plural.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Against the <qex>richesses</qex> of this world shall they have
misease of poverty.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In one hour so great <qex>riches</qex> is come to nought.</q>
<rj><qau>Rev. xviii. 17.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And for that <qex>riches</qex> where is my deserving?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Wealth; opulence; affluence; wealthiness;
richness; plenty; abundance.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1240 --></p>

<p><ent>Richesse</ent>⟦br⟧
